Felix Tran

Visualizing data

You will make lots of graphs. Most are just for you, but you will make lots of them. Start with basic graphs, then build upon them using ggplot to get better sense of your data.

Set up session by loading libraries

Create dataset

library(rnoaa)

weather_df = 
  rnoaa::meteo_pull_monitors(c("USW00094728", "USC00519397", "USS0023B17S"),
                      var = c("PRCP", "TMIN", "TMAX"), 
                      date_min = "2017-01-01",
                      date_max = "2017-12-31") %>%
  mutate(
    name = recode(id, USW00094728 = "CentralPark_NY", 
                      USC00519397 = "Waikiki_HA",
                      USS0023B17S = "Waterhole_WA"),
    tmin = tmin / 10,
    tmax = tmax / 10) %>%
  select(name, id, everything())
weather_df

Creating graphs

Making our first plot.

The first parameter is the dataset, then the aesthetics (the things you care about showing). Since we havent given the plot the geometries we want, it gives us a blank plot.

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax))

Adding geom_point() gives us a scatterplot with the specified aesthetics.

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Can be used as part of a pipeline if desired

weather_df %>% 
  filter(name == "CentralPark_NY") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point()

Plots from ggplot can be saved in a variable

weather_sp <- ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point()
weather_sp
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

More plot options

Add color to scatterplot by using name as the aesthetic.

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = name))
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Add another geom.

geom_smooth() plots a smooth line through your data. Include option to not include the SE bands around the line for this case.

Notice that the geom_smooth line is a single color because the color mapping is only within geom_point.

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = name)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Adjust alpha parameter in geom_point to adjust transperancy of points

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = name), alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

When the aesthetics are moved to ggplot, all geoms are affected.

geom_smooth graphs multiple lines with colors matching the points because the aesthetics differntiates the data into 3 clusters based on the locations (Central Park, HA, WA)

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax, color = name)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Facetting

Create separate graphs for each value of name

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmin, y = tmax, color = name)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(~ name)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

More interesting plots

Look at max temperature over the course of a year

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = date, y = tmax, color = name)) + 
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Instead of points, we can graph lines

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = date, y = tmax, color = name)) + 
  geom_line()

Add another aes option to make points small/large depending on value of precipitation (prcp)

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = date, y = tmax, color = name, size = prcp)) + 
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

More smoothing options

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = date, y = tmax, color = name, size = prcp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  facet_grid(~ name)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Univariate plots

Histograms

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmax, fill = name)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Density plot

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmax, fill = name)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Box plot

Box plot aes is y-axis for the value, not x-axis like histogram and density plots. x-axis aes will help with separate box plots

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = name, y = tmax)) +
  geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Violin plot

Convey distribution info like box and density plot combined

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = name, y = tmax)) +
  geom_violin()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

Putting ggridges to work to make ridge plots

ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmax, y = name)) +
  geom_density_ridges()
## Picking joint bandwidth of 1.84
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density_ridges).

Saving or embedding ggplots

Save as pdf

ridge_plot <- ggplot(weather_df, aes(x = tmax, y = name)) +
  geom_density_ridges()
ggsave('ridge_plot.pdf', ridge_plot, width = 8, height = 5)
## Picking joint bandwidth of 1.84
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density_ridges).

Options like this give you control for sizing/aspect ratio stuff for saved plots

knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  fig.width = 6,
  fig.asp = .6,
  out.width = "90%"
)

Last example

ggplot(weather_df, aes(y = prcp, x = name)) + geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).
